                    <h2>Setting the Stage</h2>
                    <p>In the world of web development, there are many tools and platforms that developers use. 
                        The choices can vary depending on what stage of development the project is in. Based on the system requirements we established for the 
                        Easy Entry app, we decided to use. </p>
                    <p>For the purposes of prototyping and deployment, our team used Microsoft Azure and Google App Engine to deploy the prototypes for the
                        customer and store apps respectively. Both apps are web based. 
                        </p>
                    <p>For the customer app, we used C# with an internal SQL database that we migrated to an Azure cloud database, and we deployed the app on Azure websites. 
                        For the store app side of the project, we used React and NodeJS, deployed the app on Google App Engine.  </p>
                    <p>We decided to use Microsoft's Visual Studio 2019 and Visual Studio Code to build the two apps. The customer app was built using a .NET web app, that 
                        was scaffolded in Visual Studio 2019.
                    </p>

                    <h2>The Journey </h2>
                    <p>The project took the effort of six team members. Each member had varying degrees of experience as developers, and each had their strengths and
                        weaknesses. After, deciding on the project we wanted to work on, and the vision, we started working on the project. The team met 3 times a 
                        week for 4 hours and we would break up into smaller groups of two to work on tasks and modules. 
                    </p>
                    <p>This was my first time working on a web application with a team of six developers. With no prior experience to working in teams no bigger than two, 
                        my initial challenge was finding out how a team of developers actually get coding done. As we continued meeting, we learned more about each other 
                        and worked off our strengths. To work remotely on the project, our choice of tool for communcation was Zoom and Microsoft Teams. The screen 
                        sharing feature in both Zoom and Teams helped us share our screens and at any one time depending on what needed to get done, we would have one 
                        person share the screen, and everybody else make contributions as we moved through the tasks to complete.  
                    </p>

                    <p>A big part of application development is understanding the core requirements and functionality that a client is asking for. Once the team fully 
                        understood what our core requirements were, we were easily able to split the task and module builds between us. Each team mate contributed by 
                        completing the required tasks given to them. If the client of the app was a third party, out team would have had to meet frequently with the customer 
                        with each working iteration of the app to ensure the requirements and specifications are being met. 
                    </p>

                    <p>The primary part of the project was divided into two core parts - the customer app and the store app. Within the custoer app, two team mates 
                        focused on the functinoal code and two other team mates were focused on visual design of the app. I worked on the store side of the app with another 
                        team mate and we focused on building a scanner app that would read a QR code generated by the customer app and use the data contained in the QR code to 
                        populate on the one page app and display customer information about their vaccination status.
                        <br>
                        Each week, the leadership roles rotated and we each took up our roles as best we could. 
                    </p>

                    <p>Another important aspect that was helpful throughout the entire build of the project was documentation. The requirements and specifications were 
                        clearly outlined in the Software Requ
                    </p>

                    <h2>Wrapping It App</h2>
                         <p>The vision we set out to accomplish was achieved.
                             To bring it all to a close, the two part of the group project, the customer and store side of the app were published online. The store scanner which was 
                             what I had worked on, was integrated into the customer app using a basic hyperlinked button to allow for easy testing and demoing.   
                             </p>

                    <p>With time as a constraint, we decided to leave out some features for future iterations. For instance, a sign-in form for the customer app, and an added-on security 
                        measure for the store app to verify that a customer is vaccinated.   
                        </p>                

                    <p>Overall, the entire experience of building an app as part of a team was a learning experience of the planning, orgranizing and effort 
                        needed to build an app. There was as lot to be learned from how to setup the environment, debugging, integrating modules, migrating databases, and
                    deploying. </p>

                    <p>The most challenging part of the project was migrating the customer app with an internal database to an Azure Cloud database. Completing this part of the 
                        build took almost three hours. This was because we had to figure out how to make sure the local database version was compatible with the Azure Cloud database 
                        we were working with.  
                         </p>

                    <p>The app development process and journey was well documented. This proved to be extremely useful in that it helped us keep our vision in mind 
                        of what a working prototype we were looking to build and even more importantly prevented creep programming.   
                        </p>

