                    <p>Buidling projects alone is great, but nothing beats working with a team of dedicated developers who have a common vision in mind.
                        Given a chance, I would jump right into another group project to better refine the process and apply the things I learnt in this on this project.  
                        </p>

                    <p>There is a saying that goes like this <br/>
                        <span><i>"If you want to go fast, go alone. If you want to go far go together."</i></span>
                        <br/>
                        <br/>
                        Buidling projects alone is great, but building a large robust app alone would really take its tool and time on you. But builidng an app in a team 
                        jsut makes things so much easier. <br/>
                    </p>
                        <p>In a team environment, everyone gets to pitch in on a solution making the project manageable and faster to build. There is also a certain satisfaction 
                            that comes with completing a project together.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                        The experience of working in a team is much richer as well in that you get to learn a little from everyone involved. We all walked away learning about setting up 
                        environments, scaffolding Visual Studio Projects, coding C# and JavaScript, using ReactJS and NodeJS, setting up a variety of backend servers to meet our purposes, 
                        and the joy that comes with overcoming hurdles and working out bugs in our code together. I would say this to anyone looking to start coding or any kind of development. 
                        You learn faster and move faster in a team.</p>

                        <p>Application development is group projects is very important skill to have. In a group effort, team members get to give each other feedback and carry each other 
                            when the project hits a wall. I feel group projects should emphasized at the start of any education or career as a software developer because the reality 
                            of the industry in itself is that most developers work in teams. My single greatest takeway, there is strength in numbers.
                        </p>                                                

